                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d446">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">611.1731/19: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Nicaragua</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ramer</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Managua</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1924-03-15T11:00:00-05:45">
                            <hi rend="italic">March 15, 1924—11 a.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received 11:45 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>38. Department’s 27, March 11, 5 p.m.<note n="20" xml:id="d446fn20">Not
                        printed.</note> The Nicaraguan Minister for Foreign Affairs states that his
                    Government is willing to enter into a <hi rend="italic">modus vivendi</hi>
                    through an exchange of notes mutually according unconditional
                    most-favored-nation treatment.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Ramer</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
